	(1, 'The Curse of Tutankhamun', 'One of the most famous archaeological legends, the "Curse of the Pharaohs," was sensationalized after the 1922 discovery of Tutankhamun\'s intact tomb by Howard Carter and Lord Carnarvon. The legend holds that anyone who disturbed the eternal rest of the "Boy King" would be struck by misfortune or death. The sudden death of Lord Carnarvon from an infected mosquito bite in 1923, coinciding with a mysterious power outage in Cairo, ignited global hysteria. Newspapers attributed subsequent deaths of expedition members—like archaeologist Arthur Mace and financier George Jay Gould—to the curse, often citing an inscription: "Death shall come on swift wings to him who disturbs the peace of the King." While modern science attributes the tragedies to coincidence, sealed tomb pathogens, or stress, the legend endures as a powerful narrative blending ancient mystique with the perils of violating sacred spaces. It reflects a deep-seated human fear of trespassing on the domain of the dead and the perceived power of a Pharaoh\'s divine wrath.', 1, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(2, 'The Legend of Osiris', 'The cornerstone myth of Egyptian religion, explaining death, resurrection, and kingship. Osiris, the wise and benevolent ruler of Egypt, was murdered by his jealous brother Seth, who trapped him in a chest and threw it into the Nile. Osiris\'s devoted wife-sister, Isis, retrieved his body, but Seth dismembered it into fourteen pieces, scattering them across Egypt. Isis, with her sister Nephthys, gathered the pieces (except the phallus, replaced with a gold replica) and used her powerful magic to resurrect Osiris long enough to conceive their son, Horus. Thus, Osiris became the first mummy and the eternal Lord of the Underworld (Duat), presiding over the judgment of souls. His myth established the theological basis for mummification, the hope for an afterlife, and the principle that the rightful heir (Horus) must avenge his father and restore order (Ma\'at) over chaos (Isfet).', 1, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(3, 'The Ghost of the Titanic', 'A peculiar legend based on mistaken identity. The Olympic was the nearly identical sister ship of the Titanic. After the Titanic disaster, the Olympic had a long career, including service as a troopship. Stories later emerged that the Olympic was haunted by ghosts of Titanic victims, perhaps because they looked so similar, or due to the psychological impact of the tragedy on crew who served on both ships. It\'s a meta-legend, where the ghost story is transferred to the surviving twin of the doomed vessel.', 15, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(4, 'The Flight of Icarus', 'A timeless cautionary tale about the dangers of hubris and disregarding wise counsel. The master craftsman Daedalus, imprisoned with his son Icarus in the Labyrinth by King Minos, devised an escape by air. He fashioned two pairs of wings from feathers secured with wax, warning Icarus not to fly too low (where sea dampness would clog the wings) nor too high (where the sun\'s heat would melt the wax). Overjoyed by the thrill of flight, Icarus soared ever higher, intoxicated by the freedom and proximity to the sun. The wax melted, the feathers scattered, and Icarus plummeted into the sea below, which now bears his name (the Icarian Sea). Daedalus, heartbroken, flew on to Sicily. The myth is a powerful allegory for the necessary balance between ambition and prudence, innovation and its limits, and the tragic consequences of youthful recklessness in the face of paternal wisdom.', 2, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(5, 'Ragnarök', 'The Norse apocalyptic prophecy, the "Twilight of the Gods" or "Fate of the Powers." It is not merely an end but a cyclical destruction and rebirth foretold in the Völuspá. The prophecy begins with the Fimbulwinter, three years of endless snow. Social bonds break as the wolf Sköll swallows the sun and his brother Hati the moon, plunging the world into darkness. The bonds holding Loki and the monstrous wolf Fenrir break. Fenrir advances with flames blazing from his eyes and nostrils, his lower jaw scraping the earth and upper jaw touching the stars. Loki leads the army of the dead from Hel on the ship Naglfar. The fire giants, led by Surtr, march from Muspelheim. Heimdall sounds the Gjallarhorn, summoning the gods to the final battle on the field of Vígríðr. In the ensuing cataclysm, key figures fall: Odin is devoured by Fenrir, who is then slain by Odin\'s son Víðarr; Thor kills the World Serpent Jörmungandr but succumbs to its venom after nine steps; Loki and Heimdall kill each other; Surtr immolates the world with his flaming sword. Yet, from the ashes, a new, green world emerges. The surviving gods—Víðarr, Váli, Thor\'s sons Móði and Magni—reassemble. Two humans, Líf and Lífþrasir, hidden in the world tree Yggdrasil, repopulate the earth. Ragnarök encapsulates the Norse worldview of an inevitable, heroic-endured fate, followed by renewal.', 4, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(6, 'The Legend of the Yeti', 'The Himalayan counterpart to Bigfoot. For centuries, Sherpas and mountain dwellers have told of a large, hairy, bipedal creature (meh-teh in Tibetan) inhabiting the high snows. Footprints have been found, and scalp/hand "relics" exist in monasteries (later identified as animal parts). Edmund Hillary\'s 1960 expedition found no conclusive evidence. The Yeti represents the mystery of the world\'s most forbidding mountains and the possibility of an undiscovered primate, becoming a staple of cryptozoology and mountain lore.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(7, 'The Mystery of the Bermuda Triangle', 'A region of the western North Atlantic Ocean, loosely bounded by Miami, Bermuda, and Puerto Rico, where numerous aircraft and ships are said to have disappeared under mysterious circumstances. Famous cases include Flight 19 (1945) and the USS Cyclops (1918). While the area has unpredictable weather, strong currents, and is heavily trafficked, paranormal explanations range from alien abductions and time warps to the lost city of Atlantis. Government agencies state the number of disappearances is not statistically abnormal. The legend persists as the ultimate mystery of unexplained vanishings, fueled by books, documentaries, and speculation.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(8, 'The Tale of Princess Kaguya', 'An ancient Japanese folktale (Taketori Monogatari), considered one of the earliest examples of proto-science fiction. An old bamboo cutter finds a glowing stalk containing a tiny, radiant girl, whom he and his wife raise as their own, naming her Kaguya-hime ("Radiant Princess"). She grows into a woman of unearthly beauty, attracting five noble suitors. She sets them impossible tasks (like retrieving the Buddha\'s stone bowl from India or a jewel from a dragon\'s neck). They all fail through deceit or death. Finally, the Emperor himself falls in love with her, but she rejects him too. As the moon waxes full, she reveals her true nature: she is a being from the Moon Kingdom (Tsuki no Miyako), sent to Earth as a temporary exile. Despite the Emperor\'s army trying to prevent it, envoys from the moon descend in a luminous vessel, clothe her in a feather robe of forgetfulness (hagoromo), and erase her memories of Earth. Heartbroken, her earthly parents watch as she returns to her celestial home, leaving behind a letter and an elixir of immortality for the Emperor, who burns it on the highest mountain (linking the tale to Mount Fuji). It is a story of ephemeral beauty, the sorrow of impermanence (mono no aware), and the unbridgeable gap between the mortal and celestial realms.', 8, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(9, 'Tír na nÓg', '"The Land of the Young," the most famous of the Irish Otherworlds, a paradisiacal island realm of eternal youth, beauty, and joy, where time moves differently. The legend is best told through Oisín, son of the hero Fionn mac Cumhaill. While hunting, Oisín meets Niamh Chinn Óir (Niamh of the Golden Hair), a princess from Tír na nÓg, who rides a white horse across the waves. She invites him to be her husband in her land. They journey together and live in bliss for what feels like three years. However, Oisín grows homesick. Niamh lends him her magical horse, warning him not to dismount onto Irish soil. He returns to find 300 years have passed; his father and the Fianna are long dead, only remembered in legends. Seeing men struggling to move a stone, he leans from the saddle to help, but the girth breaks and he falls to the ground. Instantly, the centuries catch up with him, and he ages into a withered old man. Before he dies, he tells his tale to Saint Patrick, bridging the pagan heroic age with the new Christian Ireland. The legend symbolizes the bittersweet choice between eternal bliss and earthly home, and the irreversible nature of time.', 7, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(10, 'The Curse of the Banshee', 'The banshee (bean sí, "woman of the fairy mound") is a female spirit whose mournful wail (keening) is an omen of death in a family, particularly the old Gaelic aristocratic families. Her cry, heard at night near the family\'s home or at a crossroads, is not a cause of death but a supernatural announcement. Descriptions vary: a gaunt woman with long silver hair and a grey cloak, a beautiful woman in a shroud, or a washerwoman at a stream scrubbing bloodstained clothes of the doomed. While usually invisible, a glimpse of her combing her hair is a bad omen; to pick up the comb she drops is to incur her wrath. The specificity of her warning—tied to a lineage, not an individual—makes her a familial psychopomp, a link between the mortal world and the Otherworld that marks the moment of a soul\'s transition. Her legend underscores the deep connection between certain families and the supernatural in Gaelic culture.', 7, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(11, 'The Curse of the Ouija Board', 'A pervasive modern legend holding that using a Ouija (or "talking") board to communicate with spirits can open a doorway to malevolent entities, leading to possession, haunting, or tragedy. Stories tell of boards spelling out threats, moving planchettes without human touch, and subsequent poltergeist activity. While psychologists attribute effects to the ideomotor effect and suggestion, the legend is reinforced by its use in horror films and religious warnings against "demonic" tools. It embodies the fear that dabbling in the occult, even as a game, has real and dangerous consequences.', 15, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(12, 'Popol Vuh', 'The sacred "Book of the Community" of the K\'iche\' Maya, a foundational epic of creation, hero twins, and the dawn of humanity. The gods attempt to create beings who will worship them. Their first attempts fail: animals cannot speak; mud men dissolve; wooden men are soulless and are destroyed in a resinous flood. The gods then discover yellow and white corn (ixim). From maize dough, they fashion the first four true men: Jaguar Quitze, Jaguar Night, Not Right Now, and Dark Jaguar. These men are too perfect, seeing and knowing all, so the gods cloud their vision. The narrative shifts to the adventures of the Hero Twins, Hunahpu and Xbalanque, who outwit the lords of Xibalba (the underworld) in a ballgame, avenging their father and uncle. They ultimately ascend to become the sun and moon. The Popol Vuh establishes corn as the sacred substance of human life, emphasizes the importance of proper reverence for the gods, and celebrates cunning and perseverance over the forces of death.', 9, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(13, 'Anansi the Spider', 'A classic Akan trickster tale explaining how stories came to belong to humanity. Originally, all stories were held by Nyame, the Sky God. Anansi, the clever spider, wanted to buy them. Nyame set an impossible price: Anansi must capture four fearsome creatures: Onini the Python, Osebo the Leopard, the Mmoboro Hornets, and Mmoatia the fairy. Using his wit, not strength, Anansi succeeds: he tricks the python by debating how to measure its length, trapping it when it stretches out; he digs a pit for the leopard; he convinces the hornets to seek shelter from "rain" by entering a calabash; and uses a sticky doll to capture the fairy. Anansi delivers all to Nyame, who keeps his word and gives all stories to Anansi. From then on, they are called "Anansesem" (Spider Stories). This legend elevates the trickster to culture hero, demonstrating that intelligence and cunning are more valuable than brute force and are the rightful keys to wisdom and narrative.', 10, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(14, 'The Creation According to the Dogon', 'The complex cosmogony of the Dogon people of Mali, involving the god Amma, the egg of the world, and amphibious progenitors. Amma, the supreme creator, shaped the Earth like a potter. His first creation was a male being, but a flaw in the process led to the presence of a feminine element, the Earth, with which Amma had to unite to correct the order. This union produced twins, the Nommo, androgynous, fish-like water spirits. However, one of the first creations, Ogo (or Yurugu, the Pale Fox), rebelled, stealing pieces of the sun\'s placenta to create an imperfect, dry Earth. To restore order, Amma sacrificed one of the Nommo, dismembering its body to scatter life across the world. The remaining Nommo were sent to Earth in an ark, along with the fundamentals of civilization—language, agriculture, craft—to become the ancestors and teachers of humanity. This intricate myth explains the origins of duality, the necessity of sacrifice for order, and the Dogon\'s profound astronomical knowledge, including the star Sirius and its companion.', 10, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(15, 'Māui and the Sun', 'A pan-Polynesian legend of the culture hero Māui using cunning to benefit humanity. In the beginning, the sun (often called Tama-nui-te-rā) raced across the sky, giving people insufficient time to work, fish, or cook. Māui decided to slow it down. With the help of his brothers or his magical grandmother, he fashioned strong ropes from flax fiber. He and his brothers journeyed to the pit where the sun rose. As the sun emerged, they lassoed its rays (legs) with the ropes, binding it fast. Māui then beat the sun with his magical jawbone club (mere pounamu in some versions) until it was weakened and agreed to move more slowly across the sky, creating the long, productive days of summer and the shorter days of winter. This legend exemplifies Māui\'s role as a benefactor of humankind, using trickery and strength to tame the forces of nature and improve the human condition.', 11, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(16, 'Pele and Hi\'iaka', 'An epic Hawaiian saga of love, jealousy, duty, and volcanic transformation. Pele, the passionate goddess of volcanoes, desired to see the distant island of Kauaʻi. She could not go herself, so she sent her favorite younger sister, Hiʻiakaikapoliopele (Hiʻiaka in the bosom of Pele), promising to keep her beloved grove of ʻōhiʻa-lehua trees and her human lover, Lohiʻau, safe during the 40-day journey. Hiʻiaka, accompanied by her friend Wahineʻōmaʻo, faced many perils, battling forest demons (moo) and reviving the dead Lohiʻau. They fell in love on the return journey. Pele, suspecting betrayal and seeing the delayed return as proof, destroyed Hiʻiaka\'s sacred forest and killed Lohiʻau. Grief-stricken and enraged, Hiʻiaka confronted Pele. In a titanic battle of volcanic and natural forces, the sisters fought across the islands. While never fully reconciled, their conflict shaped the landscape, with Pele\'s fires and Hiʻiaka\'s lush greenery eternally juxtaposed. The legend explores themes of trust, the destructive power of jealousy, and the competing forces of creation and destruction within nature and family.', 11, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(17, 'Raven and the Light (Tlingit)', 'A classic Northwest Coast creation myth, particularly of the Tlingit people. In the beginning, the world was in darkness. A great chief kept the sun, moon, and stars hidden in boxes. Raven, the ultimate trickster and transformer, determined to bring light to the world. He transformed himself into a hemlock needle floating in a stream, which the chief\'s daughter drank, becoming pregnant. The born child (Raven in disguise) was doted on by his grandfather. The child cried incessantly for the boxes to play with. Relenting, the chief gave him the stars, which Raven threw into the sky. He then cried for the moon, and did the same. Finally, he cried for the last box containing the sun. Once he had it, he transformed back into a raven and flew through the smoke hole of the house, carrying the sun. He released it into the sky, bringing daylight to the world. The story explains the origin of celestial bodies and celebrates Raven\'s cunning and his role as a benefactor—albeit a self-interested and mischievous one—of humanity.', 12, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(18, 'White Buffalo Calf Woman (Lakota)', 'The most sacred narrative of the Lakota people, bringing the foundation of their spiritual practice. During a time of famine, two scouts saw a beautiful woman approaching, dressed in white buckskin. One scout had lustful thoughts; he was consumed by a cloud. The other showed respect. She identified herself as Ptesáŋwiŋ (White Buffalo Calf Woman) and brought a sacred bundle. She taught the people the Seven Sacred Rites, including the sweat lodge (inípi) and the vision quest (hanbléčheyapi). Most importantly, she presented the Sacred Pipe (čhaŋnúŋpa), showing how its stem (wood, male) and bowl (stone, female) represented all of creation. She explained that smoking the pipe would carry prayers to Wakan Tanka (the Great Mystery). As she left, she rolled upon the earth, transforming into a black, red, and yellow buffalo before finally becoming a white buffalo calf, promising to return. Her gift established the covenant between the Lakota and the divine, making the pipe the central object of prayer and ceremony.', 12, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(19, 'The Mummy Queen of Lo Ch\'i P\'ing', 'A persistent Chinese legend and alleged historical account of a Tang Dynasty noblewoman who was buried alive as a sacrifice or due to a premature burial ritual. The tale, often told as a local ghost story, claims her spirit could not rest. Her perfectly preserved mummy was said to be discovered in an untouched tomb, surrounded by treasures and curse inscriptions. Those who disturbed her rest were afflicted by a "tomb sickness"—mysterious ailments, bad luck, or death. The legend, while likely a composite of various tomb discoveries and folklore, taps into universal fears of the vengeful dead and the taboos surrounding grave robbery. It serves as a Chinese parallel to the "Curse of the Pharaohs," warning against violating ancient sepulchers and disrespecting the ancestors.', 13, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(20, 'The Two Lovers of the River', 'One of China\'s great love stories, explaining the origin of the Qixi Festival (Chinese Valentine\'s Day). Zhinü, the Weaver Girl (the star Vega), a daughter of the Jade Emperor, descended to bathe in a river. Niulang, a poor cowherd (the star Altair), was advised by his magical ox to steal her heavenly robes. Without them, she could not return. They fell in love, married, and had two children. When the Jade Emperor discovered this, he was furious and ordered Zhinü back to heaven. Using the hide of his dead ox, Niulang flew after her with their children. The Empress Mother (or Jade Emperor) created the Milky Way (Yinhe, "Silver River") to separate them forever. Moved by their love, magpies formed a bridge across the galaxy once a year, on the 7th day of the 7th lunar month, allowing them to reunite for a single night. The legend is a timeless tale of love across an impossible divide and the annual celestial event that commemorates it.', 13, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(21, 'The Devil\'s Bridge (Bulgaria)', 'A widespread European folktale motif (Type 1191) found in Bulgaria, often associated with specific ancient bridges like the one over the Arda River. The story varies but follows a common pattern: a master builder is struggling to construct a crucial bridge that keeps collapsing. The Devil (satana) appears and offers to complete the bridge in a single night in exchange for the soul of the first living being to cross it. The builder agrees. At dawn, the bridge stands perfect. Wracked with guilt, the builder devises a trick: he lures a dog, cat, or rooster across the bridge first, thus cheating the Devil of a human soul. Enraged but bound by his word, the Devil vanishes, sometimes leaving a hoof-print or claw-mark on the stones. The legend serves as a folk explanation for remarkable engineering feats, emphasizes cleverness over demonic pacts, and often contains a moral about outwitting evil.', 14, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(22, 'The Highgate Vampire', 'A British media sensation of the 1970s. After reports of a tall, dark figure haunting Highgate Cemetery in London, vampire hunters and occultists (notably David Farrant and Sean Manchester) publicly claimed a medieval vampire noble was buried there and needed to be staked. The hype led to vandalism, arrests, and a live TV hunt. While likely stemming from local ghost stories and gothic imagination, it created a modern, public "vampire panic" in the heart of London, demonstrating the enduring power of the vampire archetype.', 15, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(23, 'The Girl in the Well', 'A Mexican urban legend, particularly from Veracruz. It tells of drivers on a lonely road at night who hear the voice of a little girl crying for help from a nearby well. If they stop and approach, the voice leads them deeper into danger, or the "girl" is revealed to be a malevolent spirit. In some versions, those who try to rescue her fall in and die. It\'s a classic "phantom hitchhiker" variant, using the imagery of a vulnerable child to lure victims, playing on fears of roadside dangers and the guilt of not helping.', 15, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(24, 'The Flatwoods Monster', 'A classic American "close encounter" legend from the early UFO era. On September 12, 1952, in Flatwoods, West Virginia, a group of boys and a mother saw a bright object crash on a hill. Investigating with a flashlight, they encountered a towering (10+ foot) entity: its head was red and shaped like the ace of spades or a heart, with glowing, non-human eyes beneath it. The body was dark, possibly a cowl or dress, and it seemed to float or glide. It emitted a hissing sound and a foul, metallic odor that made witnesses nauseous. The entity retreated towards a pulsating, acrid-smelling "globe of fire." The story was reported in newspapers nationwide, and an investigation attributed it to a meteor and a startled barn owl. However, the vivid, detailed description of the monster—so different from the "little green men" of the time—captured the public imagination, cementing it as a unique cryptid/alien hybrid in American folklore, representing the mystery and terror of the unknown during the Cold War.', 15, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(25, 'The Book of Thoth', 'An Egyptian legend, part of the Setna Cycle, about the perils of forbidden knowledge. Prince Setna Khaemwas, a famed magician, learns of a magical book written by the god Thoth himself, hidden in a series of nested chests at the bottom of the Nile in a tomb guarded by supernatural traps. The book promised to grant the reader the power to understand animals, see the gods, and command the heavens. Despite warnings from the ghost of its previous owner (who suffered tragedy), Setna retrieves it. He gains great power but is soon haunted by visions of a beautiful woman, Tabubu, who seduces him into giving away all he owns and even killing his children. He realizes it\'s an illusion, a curse from the book. To break it, he must return the book and perform proper burial rites for the original owner\'s family. The legend is a cautionary tale about the hubris of seeking god-like knowledge and the moral responsibility that comes with power.', 1, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(26, 'The Battle of Horus and Seth', 'An epic, 80-year-long divine legal battle for the succession of Osiris\'s throne. After Osiris\'s murder, his son Horus (backed by Isis) claimed kingship, but his uncle Set, god of chaos, argued he was the stronger candidate. The case was tried before the Ennead of gods. The proceedings were tumultuous: Set gouged out Horus\'s eye (later restored by Thoth), and Horus castrated Set. Isis\'s clever interventions repeatedly swayed the court in Horus\'s favor, infuriating Set. The conflict spilled onto the earthly plane, representing the struggle between order (Horus, the fertile Nile) and chaos (Set, the desert). Ultimately, the gods appealed to the primordial goddess Neith, who ruled in favor of Horus. The aged sun god Ra, who favored Set, reluctantly accepted the verdict. Horus was crowned king of the living, and Set was given the stormy sky and foreign lands as his domain. The myth legitimizes Pharaohs as the living Horus and explains the eternal tension between Egypt\'s cultivated land and the hostile desert.', 1, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(27, 'The Destruction of Mankind', 'A dramatic myth from the tomb of Seti I, explaining how the benevolent goddess Hathor became the vengeful Sekhmet. In his old age, the sun god Ra grew angry that humanity was plotting against him. He sent his "Eye"—the goddess Hathor—in her fierce, lioness form (Sekhmet) to punish them. She descended, reveling in slaughter, drenching the fields in blood. Ra, seeing the scale of the carnage and fearing she would annihilate all humans, repented. To stop her, he ordered his priests to brew 7,000 jars of beer dyed red with ochre (or pomegranate juice) and pour it over the fields. Sekhmet, mistaking it for blood, drank it, became intoxicated, and fell asleep. When she awoke, her bloodlust was gone, and she returned to Ra as the gentle Hathor. The myth explains the dual nature of the goddess, the origins of ritual beer offerings, and the belief that the gods could be both merciful and wrathful, requiring appeasement.', 1, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(28, 'Pandora\'s Box', 'Hesiod\'s foundational myth explaining the origin of evil in the world. After Prometheus stole fire for humanity, Zeus ordered the creation of the first woman as punishment. Hephaestus molded her from earth and water; Athena clothed her; Aphrodite gave her grace; and Hermes gave her "a shameless mind and a deceitful nature." Her name was Pandora, "All-Gifted." She was given a large jar (pithos, mistranslated as "box" by Erasmus) and told never to open it. Driven by curiosity (or, in some versions, sent by Zeus with the jar as a dowry), she lifted the lid. From it flew all the evils that plague humanity—sickness, toil, sorrow. Horrified, she slammed the lid shut, trapping only Hope (Elpis) inside. The myth is a deeply misogynistic etiological tale, blaming woman for the world\'s ills, but also explores themes of divine retribution, curiosity, and the ambiguous nature of hope—whether it is a blessing left for humanity or the cruelest evil of all, keeping humans striving in a world of suffering.', 2, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(29, 'The Labors of Heracles', 'The quintessential heroic penance. Driven mad by Hera, Heracles killed his wife and children. To atone, the Delphic Oracle commanded him to serve his cousin, King Eurystheus of Tiryns, for twelve years, performing any task set for him. These became the Twelve Labors: 1) Slay the Nemean Lion (skin invulnerable to weapons). 2) Slay the nine-headed Lernaean Hydra (heads regrew). 3) Capture the Ceryneian Hind (golden-horned, sacred to Artemis). 4) Capture the Erymanthian Boar. 5) Clean the Augean stables (30 years of dung) in one day. 6) Drive away the Stymphalian Birds (man-eating, bronze-feathered). 7) Capture the Cretan Bull. 8) Steal the Mares of Diomedes (man-eating). 9) Obtain the girdle of Hippolyta, Queen of the Amazons. 10) Steal the cattle of the monster Geryon. 11) Steal the golden apples of the Hesperides. 12) Capture Cerberus from the Underworld. Through sheer strength, courage, and occasional cunning (and help from his nephew Iolaus on the Hydra), Heracles succeeded, achieving apotheosis (becoming a god) and symbolizing the triumph of heroic effort over monstrous adversity and personal tragedy.', 2, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(30, 'The Abduction of Persephone', 'The central myth of the Eleusinian Mysteries, explaining the seasons. Persephone (Kore, "the Maiden"), daughter of Demeter (goddess of agriculture), was gathering flowers when Hades, god of the underworld, burst forth in his chariot and abducted her to be his queen. Demeter, in her grief, caused a worldwide famine, neglecting her duties. Helios, the sun, told her what happened. Demeter wandered in disguise until she came to Eleusis. Meanwhile, Persephone, having eaten a few pomegranate seeds in the underworld, was bound to it. Zeus mediated: Persephone would spend part of the year (winter/autumn) with Hades and the rest (spring/summer) with Demeter. Her return brings spring\'s rebirth; her departure brings winter\'s dormancy. The myth is a profound exploration of mother-daughter bonds, the cycle of life and death, and the origins of sacred rituals promising initiates a blessed afterlife.', 2, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(31, 'The Forging of Mjölnir', 'A tale of divine mischief and dwarven craftsmanship. Loki, after cutting off the golden hair of Thor\'s wife Sif as a prank, promised to get her even better hair from the dwarves. He went to the sons of Ivaldi, who forged not only golden hair that grew like real hair, but also the ship Skíðblaðnir for Freyr and the spear Gungnir for Odin. Boasting, Loki bet his head with the dwarf brothers Brokkr and Sindri that they could not make three equally good items. While they worked at their forge, Brokkr pumped the bellows. Loki, in the form of a fly, bit Brokkr to disrupt him. Despite the bites, they created: the golden-bristled boar Gullinbursti for Freyr, the golden ring Draupnir for Odin (which multiplied itself), and the mighty hammer Mjölnir for Thor. Its only flaw was a short handle, due to Loki\'s final bite. The gods judged the hammer the greatest treasure, for it would protect them from giants. Brokkr claimed Loki\'s head, but Loki argued the head was his but not the neck. Brokkr sewed Loki\'s lips shut instead. Thus, Thor gained his iconic weapon, and Loki was punished—for a time.', 4, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(32, 'The Theft of Thor\'s Hammer', 'A comedic tale of cross-dressing and cunning. The giant Thrym stole Thor\'s hammer, Mjölnir, and demanded the goddess Freyja as his bride in exchange. Freyja refused, and the gods were in crisis. Heimdall suggested Thor dress as Freyja and go to Jötunheimr with Loki as his "maidservant." Reluctantly, Thor donned a bridal gown and veil. At the wedding feast, the disguised "Freyja" ate an entire ox, eight salmon, and drank three casks of mead, astonishing Thrym. Loki, as the maid, explained that "Freyja" had not eaten for eight days in anticipation. When Thrym lifted the veil to kiss his bride, he was met with Thor\'s burning eyes. Loki again explained it was "love-fire." The moment the hammer was brought out to hallow the bride, Thor seized it, slaughtered Thrym and all the giants, and returned in triumph. The story highlights Thor\'s brute force and Loki\'s quick-wittedness, subverting gender norms for a greater good.', 4, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(33, 'The Binding of Fenrir', 'A tale of prophecy, trickery, and necessary betrayal. The gods, forewarned of the danger posed by Loki\'s wolf-son Fenrir, raised him in Asgard. He grew monstrously strong. To control him, they challenged him to break chains, calling it a test of strength. He easily broke two mighty fetters, Leyding and Dromi. The gods then enlisted the dwarves to create an unbreakable fetter from six impossible things: the sound of a cat\'s footfall, a woman\'s beard, mountain roots, a bear\'s sinews, a fish\'s breath, and a bird\'s spittle. The result was a silken ribbon called Gleipnir. Fenrir, suspicious, agreed to be bound only if one of the gods placed a hand in his mouth as a pledge of good faith. The god Týr, known for his courage, did so. When Fenrir found he could not break free, he bit off Týr\'s hand. The gods tied Gleipnir to a rock (Gjöll) deep in the earth, and placed a sword between Fenrir\'s jaws to keep them open. He howls there until Ragnarök. The story demonstrates the price of securing the present (Týr\'s sacrifice) against a prophesied future doom.', 4, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(34, 'Momotarō', 'A beloved Japanese folktale of a miraculous child who becomes a hero. An old, childless woman finds a giant peach floating down a river. When her husband tries to cut it open, a baby boy emerges, naming himself Momotarō ("Peach Firstborn"). He grows strong and kind. When demons (oni) from a distant island terrorize the land, teenage Momotarō sets off to defeat them. His parents give him millet dumplings (kibidango). On the way, he befriends a talking dog, monkey, and pheasant by sharing his dumplings. With his animal allies, he raids the demons\' island. Using the animals\' unique abilities (dog bites, monkey scratches, pheacock pecks) and his own strength, they defeat the demons. Momotarō retrieves the stolen treasure and returns home a hero. The story emphasizes virtues of courage, justice, and the power of cooperation, serving as a popular allegory for national strength in later periods.', 8, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(35, 'Urashima Tarō', 'A Japanese Rip Van Winkle-style tale about the relativity of time and the irrevocable nature of choices. A kind fisherman, Urashima Tarō, rescues a turtle from torment. In gratitude, the turtle (a transformed princess, Otohime) takes him to the undersea Dragon Palace (Ryūgū-jō). He is entertained for what feels like three days. Homesick, he prepares to leave. Otohime gives him a layered box (tamatebako), begging him never to open it. Returning to his village, he finds centuries have passed; everything and everyone he knew is gone. In despair or forgetfulness, he opens the box. A puff of white smoke (his stored age) escapes, and he instantly transforms into an ancient, white-haired man and dies. In some versions, he becomes a crane. The tale warns against curiosity and breaking promises, and poignantly illustrates the theme that one can never truly return to a lost past.', 8, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(36, 'The Legend of Yamata no Orochi', 'The myth of the storm god Susanoo\'s heroic deed after being banished from heaven. Arriving in Izumo, he finds an old couple weeping. Their eight daughters have been devoured, one by one each year, by an eight-headed, eight-tailed serpent (Yamata no Orochi), and the last, Kushinada-hime, is next. Susanoo agrees to slay the monster if he can marry her. He instructs the parents to brew eightfold sake (sake), place it in eight vats, and build a fence with eight gates. The serpent arrives, dips each head into a vat, and drinks itself into a stupor. Susanoo then cuts it to pieces. In its tail, he finds the legendary sword Ame-no-Murakumo-no-Tsurugi ("Sword of the Gathering Clouds of Heaven"), later named Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi, one of the Three Imperial Regalia of Japan. He presents it to his sister Amaterasu as a reconciliation offering. The myth establishes Susanoo as a powerful, if chaotic, hero and explains the divine origin of the sacred sword.', 8, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(37, 'Cú Chulainn', 'The central hero of the Ulster Cycle, renowned for his superhuman battle frenzy (ríastrad). Born Sétanta, he earned the name Cú Chulainn ("Hound of Culann") as a child by killing the smith Culann\'s ferocious guard dog and offering to serve as its replacement until a new one was grown. Trained by the warrior-woman Scáthach, he gained his famed spear, the Gáe Bolg. His greatest feat was the Táin Bó Cúailnge (Cattle Raid of Cooley), where he single-handedly defended Ulster (whose warriors were cursed with labor pains) against the armies of Queen Medb of Connacht. Using guerrilla tactics and his terrifying warp-spasm—where his body contorted into a monstrous shape—he held the ford against champion after champion. The saga ends with his tragic death, tricked into breaking his geasa (taboos) and fighting against overwhelming odds, tied to a standing stone so he would die on his feet. He embodies the ideal of the youthful, tragic, supremely skilled warrior whose fury is both a gift and a curse.', 7, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(38, 'Loch Ness Monster', 'Scotland\'s most famous cryptid legend. Reports of a large creature inhabiting the deep, murky waters of Loch Ness date back to St. Columba\'s Life in the 6th century. Modern interest exploded in 1933 after a new road provided clear views of the loch, and a couple reported seeing an enormous creature cross the road and slide into the water. The following year, the famous "Surgeon\'s Photograph" (later revealed as a hoax) cemented the image of a long-necked, plesiosaur-like creature. Despite numerous sonar surveys, photographs, and searches, no conclusive evidence has been found. Scientific explanations range from misidentified seals, sturgeon, or floating logs to wave phenomena and psychological suggestibility. "Nessie" persists as a global icon of mystery, driving tourism and symbolizing the possibility of hidden wonders in an increasingly explored world.', 14, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(39, 'The Hunt for Twrch Trwyth', 'A fantastical and violent boar hunt from the Welsh Mabinogion. The boar Twrch Trwyth is no ordinary beast but a cursed king transformed, with poisonous bristles and accompanied by seven fierce young boars. To win the daughter of the giant Ysbaddaden, Culhwch must complete impossible tasks, including obtaining the comb and shears from between Twrch Trwyth\'s ears. King Arthur and his men pursue the boar across Ireland and Wales in an epic, destructive chase. The boar kills many warriors. Eventually, with great effort and loss, they drive him into the sea at Cornwall, where he disappears. The hunt is less about the quarry and more about a display of heroic (and brutal) endeavor, testing the limits of Arthur\'s court and their commitment to a sworn oath.', 7, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(40, 'The Fall of Tollan', 'The legendary downfall of the Toltec capital under its priest-king Quetzalcoatl (Ce Acatl Topiltzin). A model of Tollan was a city of great wisdom, art, and peace. However, the dark god Tezcatlipoca ("Smoking Mirror") set out to corrupt it and destroy Quetzalcoatl. Through a series of tricks, he exploited Quetzalcoatl\'s virtues. He got him drunk with pulque, making him break his celibacy. He showed him his aged face in a mirror, shaming him. Finally, Tezcatlipoca and his allies drove Quetzalcoatl from the city in disgrace. The king burned his palace of turquoise and shell, buried his treasures, and departed eastward towards the sea, promising to return one day. With his departure, Tollan fell into decadence and was eventually abandoned. The myth explains the historical fall of a great city, the struggle between opposing cosmic forces (feathered serpent vs. smoking mirror), and seeded the later Mesoamerican belief in the returning god, tragically exploited during the Spanish conquest.', 9, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(41, 'The Creation of Man', 'A central narrative in Mesoamerican myth. In the Aztec version of the Five Suns, the gods attempted to create beings who would worship them. After failed attempts with ash and wood, Quetzalcoatl journeyed to the underworld (Mictlan) to retrieve the precious bones of previous races. He ground them and mixed them with his own blood (or the blood of the gods), creating the maize-fed humans of the Fifth Sun. The Maya Popol Vuh provides a more detailed version: after failed attempts with mud and wood, the gods discovered yellow and white corn. The Four Fathers (the first humans) were formed from maize dough by gods like Huracan. They were perfect, seeing and knowing all, so the gods limited their vision to preserve their own supremacy. This creation establishes corn as the sacred substance of life and humanity\'s purpose: to sustain the gods through worship and sacrifice.', 9, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(42, 'Quetzalcoatl\'s Journey to the Underworld', 'A key episode in the creation of the current human era. After the destruction of the previous world, Quetzalcoatl, in the form of the wind god Ehecatl, descended to Mictlan, the realm of the death lord Mictlantecuhtli. He asked for the bones of the ancestors to create a new race. Mictlantecuhtli agreed, but only if Quetzalcoatl could circle his realm four times while blowing a conch shell without holes. Quetzalcoatl summoned worms to drill holes in the shell and bees to enter and make it roar, thus completing the task. He took the bones, but Mictlantecuhtli sent his minions to dig a pit to trap him. Quetzalcoatl fell, and the bones were scattered and broken (explaining why humans come in different sizes). He gathered them, escaped, and took them to Tamoanchan. There, the goddess Cihuacoatl ground the bones, and the gods let their blood fall upon the meal, creating the people of the Fifth Sun. This myth highlights Quetzalcoatl\'s role as a culture hero and the sacred, costly substance of human life.', 9, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(43, 'Creation According to Yoruba', 'A myth explaining human imperfections. The supreme god Olodumare tasked Obatala (or Orishala), the god of creation and purity, with molding human bodies from clay on Earth. Before departing, Obatala prepared palm wine as an offering. On his journey, he grew thirsty and drank the wine, becoming intoxicated. In his drunken state, he began fashioning humans, but his work was flawed—he created those with disabilities, deformities, and illnesses. When he sobered and saw his work, he was filled with remorse. He vowed to become the special protector of those born with differences. Olodumare then breathed life (emi) into the figures. This myth teaches compassion, assigns a divine protector to the vulnerable, and provides an etiology for human physical variety, attributing it not to evil but to a divine mistake.', 10, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(44, 'The Descent of Shango', 'The story of the deification of the fourth king of the Oyo Empire into the orisha of thunder and lightning. As king, Shango was a powerful but sometimes unjust ruler. After a magical accident (involving a destructive spell he learned from a sorcerer) caused the death of his own family and turned his people against him, Shango was consumed by guilt and shame. He left his palace and, according to the most common version, went to a forest and hanged himself from an ayan (shea butter) tree. His followers, refusing to believe their king had committed suicide, declared he had ascended to the heavens by his own will, becoming one with the thunder. Thus, Shango did not die but transformed into an immortal orisha. His story explains the historical king\'s mysterious end and establishes the powerful, fiery, and righteous (yet tragically flawed) nature of the deity.', 10, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(45, 'The Hare and the Moon', 'A widespread African folktale with many variations (found among the Bantu, San, and others) explaining animal features and lunar markings. In one common version, the moon sends the hare to deliver a message of immortality to humanity: "Just as I die and am reborn, so shall you." The hare, either forgetful or mischievous, delivers the opposite message: "Just as I die and do not return, so shall you." When the moon learns of the error, it strikes the hare on the lip, splitting it. In another version, the hare insults the moon, who throws an axe or a stick at it, creating the lip and the marks on the moon\'s face (the "hare in the moon"). The story explains the hare\'s distinctive philtrum, the markings on the moon, and often carries a moral about the consequences of lies, forgetfulness, or disrespect.', 10, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(46, 'The Fishing Up of Islands', 'The great creation myth of Polynesia, particularly New Zealand (Aotearoa). Māui, fishing with his brothers, used his magical fishhook (made from his grandmother\'s jawbone, Murirangawhenua) and his own blood as bait. He convinced his brothers to paddle far out to sea, beyond the sight of land. There, he cast his line, chanting powerful incantations. He hooked something immense—the great fish, Te Ika-a-Māui (The Fish of Māui). As he hauled it up, he told his brothers not to look back. But one did, breaking the tapu (sacred restriction). The line snapped, and the fish, instead of being drawn smoothly to the surface, broke apart. Its body became the North Island of New Zealand, its jagged mountains the result of the brothers\' subsequent chopping at the "fish." His canoe became the South Island (Te Waka a Māui). This myth is a foundational charter story, giving a divine and heroic origin to the landscape.', 11, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(47, 'The Search for Fire', 'A myth explaining the origin of fire for humanity. In the beginning, fire was guarded by the kūmara (sweet potato) goddess, Mahuika, or by birds in the underworld. Māui, seeking fire for humans, went to his ancestor Mahuika and asked for a flame. She gave him one of her fiery fingernails (or toenails). Māui, testing her or playing a trick, extinguished it and asked for another. This repeated until she had only one nail left. Enraged, she threw the last one at him, setting the world ablaze. Māui, in some versions, called upon the rain to quench the fires, or transformed into a hawk to escape. In the chaos, he managed to hide a spark in certain trees (like the kaikōmako or māhoe). He then showed humans how to rub these woods together to create fire. The myth highlights Māui\'s role as a trickster-benefactor and provides an etiological explanation for why friction fire-starting works with specific trees.', 11, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(48, 'Hina and the Moon', 'Several Polynesian legends explain the presence of a woman (Hina) in the moon. In one Hawaiian version, Hina, wife of the eel-god (or ordinary man) Kuna, was constantly harassed by him. She fled up a rainbow to the moon for safety and eternal peace. In a Māori version, Hina (Hine-te-iwaiwa), weary of her earthly life and the toils of making tapa cloth, climbed the moon\'s path (the Ara-whānui-a-Rangi) and remains there, often seen with her beating mallet. In Tahiti, she is the goddess of the moon who grants wishes. These stories link the moon to feminine energy, domestic crafts, refuge, and the cycle of time, offering an explanation for the perceived figure on the lunar surface.', 11, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(49, 'The First Corn', 'A common motif in Native American mythology, where a heroic figure obtains corn from a guarded source. In a Cherokee version, an old woman (Selu) produced corn and beans from her body. After her suspicious sons spied on her and killed her, they followed her dying instructions to clear and drag the ground where she was buried, and corn sprouted. In a Pueblo version, the Corn Maidens, ethereal beings, brought corn but were driven away by the people\'s disrespect. Through prayer and ritual, they were coaxed back to share their gift. In a Plains version, a young man follows a beautiful woman (the Corn Spirit) into the earth and returns with seed. These legends establish corn as a sacred, life-giving gift from the spirit world, obtained through sacrifice, respect, and proper ritual, not mere agriculture.', 12, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(50, 'The Ghost Dance', 'A historical and spiritual movement among Plains tribes in the late 19th century, founded by the Paiute prophet Wovoka (Jack Wilson). After a vision during a solar eclipse, Wovoka preached a message of hope: if people lived righteously, performed the Ghost Dance, and sang the sacred songs, a cataclysm would remove the white settlers, the buffalo would return, and deceased ancestors would be resurrected to live in a renewed, paradisiacal earth. The dance spread rapidly, especially among the Lakota, where it took on a more militant interpretation. U.S. authorities, fearing insurrection, banned it. The movement culminated tragically in the Wounded Knee Massacre of 1890. As a legend, it represents a profound moment of prophetic hope, cultural resilience, and tragic confrontation in the face of cultural annihilation.', 12, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(51, 'How Raven Got Its Color', 'Another trickster tale explaining animal traits. Originally, Raven was pure white. In his quest to bring light to the world (or for other selfish reasons), he often flew too close to the newly placed sun. The intense heat and soot from the cosmic fires blackened his feathers permanently. In some versions, he was burned while stealing the sun or fire. In others, he was punished by the tricked chief for his theft. His once-beautiful white plumage was forever charred, leaving only a few white feathers at the nape of his neck as a reminder. This story explains the raven\'s glossy black color and often serves as a moral about the consequences of daring, thievery, or getting too close to powerful, dangerous forces.', 12, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(52, 'The Great Yu and the Flood', 'A central Chinese foundational myth, blending history and legend. In the time of Emperor Yao, a catastrophic flood inundated the land. Yao\'s minister Gun tried to control it by building dikes, but failed after nine years and was executed. His son, Yu, took over. Yu adopted a new strategy: dredging channels to guide the waters to the sea. He labored tirelessly for 13 years, "passing his door without entering," his hands and feet calloused. He married but saw his son only briefly. With the help of a yellow dragon and a black turtle, he divided the land into the Nine Provinces, controlled the floods, and made the land fertile. His success earned him the mantle of emperor, founding the semi-legendary Xia Dynasty. Yu represents the ideal of the self-sacrificing public servant, the triumph of疏导 over堵塞 (dredging over damming), and the civilizing hero who tamed China\'s chaotic waters.', 13, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(53, 'The Weaver and the Cowherd', 'One of China\'s great love stories, explaining the origin of the Qixi Festival (Chinese Valentine\'s Day). Zhinü, the Weaver Girl (the star Vega), a daughter of the Jade Emperor, descended to bathe in a river. Niulang, a poor cowherd (the star Altair), was advised by his magical ox to steal her heavenly robes. Without them, she could not return. They fell in love, married, and had two children. When the Jade Emperor discovered this, he was furious and ordered Zhinü back to heaven. Using the hide of his dead ox, Niulang flew after her with their children. The Empress Mother (or Jade Emperor) created the Milky Way (Yinhe, "Silver River") to separate them forever. Moved by their love, magpies formed a bridge across the galaxy once a year, on the 7th day of the 7th lunar month, allowing them to reunite for a single night. The legend is a timeless tale of love across an impossible divide and the annual celestial event that commemorates it.', 13, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(54, 'The Monkey King', 'The protagonist of the 16th-century Chinese epic Journey to the West. Born from a stone nourished by heaven and earth, Sun Wukong (the "Monkey Awakened to Emptiness") gains supernatural powers through Taoist practice: shape-shifting, cloud-somersaulting, and cloning from his hairs. He proclaims himself "Great Sage Equal to Heaven," wreaks havoc in the celestial bureaucracy, and cannot be killed. The Buddha finally imprisons him under Five Elements Mountain for 500 years. He is later released to escort the monk Xuanzang to India to fetch Buddhist scriptures. Throughout the journey, his boundless energy, pride, and cunning are channeled (with the help of a golden headband that induces headaches) into overcoming demons and obstacles. He ultimately achieves Buddhahood. Sun Wukong is an icon of rebellious spirit, transformative power, and the journey from chaotic id to enlightened discipline.', 13, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(55, 'The Bronze Horseman', 'A Russian legend based on the 1782 equestrian statue of Peter the Great in St. Petersburg, immortalized in Pushkin\'s 1833 poem The Bronze Horseman. The poem tells of a poor clerk, Yevgeny, who loses his love in the great flood of 1824. Mad with grief, he blames the statue of the city\'s founder and shakes his fist at it. That night, he imagines the statue comes to life, its bronze horse galloping through the streets to pursue him in a relentless, symbolic chase representing the crushing power of the state and history over the individual. The legend, fueled by the poem, holds that the statue protects the city from invaders and floods, but also embodies the awesome, terrifying, and inescapable legacy of Peter\'s will, watching over the city he built on bones.', 14, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(56, 'The Sunken City of Kitezh', 'The Russian "Atlantis," a legend of divine protection. According to tradition, the city of Greater Kitezh on the shores of Lake Svetloyar was a place of great piety. When Batu Khan\'s Mongol hordes approached in the 13th century, the prayers of its citizens caused God to protect the city: it was enveloped in a mist and sank beneath the lake waters, becoming invisible. Its bells can still be heard by the pure of heart on quiet nights, and the righteous may catch a glimpse of its glowing domes in the lake\'s depths. The city is said to rise again in Russia\'s greatest hour of need. This legend transforms a historical defeat into a spiritual victory, creating a myth of a hidden, sacred Russia preserved from defilement.', 14, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(57, 'The Curse of Anastasia', 'A 20th-century legend born from historical mystery. After the Bolsheviks executed Tsar Nicholas II and his family in 1918, rumors persisted that his youngest daughter, Grand Duchess Anastasia, had survived. Numerous impostors emerged, most famously Anna Anderson, who claimed to be Anastasia for decades. The legend wove a tale of miraculous escape, hidden identity, and a royal heir living in obscurity, often coupled with a "curse" on those who had murdered the family or on the Romanov dynasty itself. The mystery was largely solved in the 1990s with DNA testing on the remains, confirming the entire family\'s death. However, the legend endures as a romantic story of survival and lost royalty, reflecting public fascination with the tragic end of an empire.', 14, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(58, 'The Mystery of the Nazca Lines', 'Massive geoglyphs etched into the desert plains of southern Peru, created by the Nazca culture between 500 BCE and 500 CE. They depict animals (hummingbird, spider, monkey), plants, and geometric shapes, some over 1,200 feet long. Their purpose remains debated: astronomical calendar, ritual pathways related to water and fertility, or offerings to deities viewable from the sky. Their sheer scale and precision, best viewed from the air, have also fueled fringe theories about ancient astronauts. The true legend is the mystery of their creation and meaning, a testament to the ingenuity of a pre-Columbian civilization.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(59, 'The Suicide House in Singapore', 'A recurring urban legend, often attached to a specific address (like the "old house on Mount Pleasant" or "the bungalow at..."). The tale describes a house where a series of unrelated tenants or visitors, often over decades, have taken their own lives in similar ways. The cause is attributed to a malevolent spirit (a pontianak or a hantu), a feng shui flaw, or a curse from a past murder or suicide on the property. Authorities or owners try to renovate or bless the house, but the deaths continue. This legend, found in various forms globally, serves as a modern expression of the "haunted house" archetype, projecting societal anxieties about mental health and unexplained tragedies onto a specific, stigmatized location.', 15, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(60, 'Nostradamus\' 2025 Prophecy', 'A modern example of the continual reinvention of Nostradamus\'s cryptic 16th-century quatrains. Certain verses (like Century I, Quatrain 50, or Century X, Quatrain 72) are interpreted by conspiracy theorists and popular media as predicting a major catastrophe for 2025. Interpretations range from a third world war, a colossal natural disaster, a pole shift, or an alien invasion. The "prophecy" gains traction online, especially during times of global uncertainty. It demonstrates how Nostradamus\'s vague, poetic writings are retrofitted to current fears, creating a perpetual cycle of apocalyptic expectation. The legend is less about the historical figure and more about the human need to find pattern, meaning, and warning in an unpredictable world.', 15, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(61, 'The Churning of the Ocean of Milk', 'A pivotal creation myth from Hindu texts like the Mahabharata and Purana. To obtain the nectar of immortality (amrita), the devas (gods) and asuras (demons) temporarily allied. Using the serpent Vasuki as a rope and Mount Mandara as a churning rod, they churned the primordial ocean. Vishnu, in his Kurma (tortoise) avatar, supported the mountain. From the churning, numerous treasures (ratnas) emerged: the lethal poison Halahala (swallowed by Shiva), the divine cow Kamadhenu, the goddess Lakshmi, the moon, the divine elephant Airavata, and finally, the physician Dhanvantari with the pot of amrita. A fierce battle ensued for the nectar. Vishnu, as the enchantress Mohini, distracted the asuras and distributed the amrita only to the devas, ensuring their immortality and supremacy. The myth explains the origin of many divine beings and embodies the concept of obtaining great boons through immense collective effort, albeit with inevitable conflict over the prize.', 5, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(62, 'The Descent of the Ganges', 'A story of filial piety and divine intervention. King Bhagiratha\'s ancestors, 60,000 sons of King Sagara, were reduced to ashes by the wrath of the sage Kapila. They could only attain salvation if the celestial river Ganga flowed over their ashes. King Bhagiratha performed severe penance for millennia, first to Brahma, who agreed to send Ganga down, and then to Shiva, as only he could withstand the river\'s immense force. Shiva allowed Ganga to fall onto his matted locks, breaking her descent into gentle streams. Thus tamed, Ganga followed Bhagiratha\'s chariot to the sea and then to the netherworld, liberating his ancestors. This myth establishes the Ganges\' divine origin, its purifying power, and Shiva\'s role as the benevolent controller of nature\'s ferocity. It is a cornerstone of the river\'s sacred status in Hinduism.', 5, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(63, 'The Marriage of Shiva and Parvati', 'The story of the ultimate ascetic\'s conquest by love and devotion. After the death of his first wife, Sati, Shiva withdrew into deep, solitary meditation. Meanwhile, the demon Tarakasura could only be killed by a son of Shiva. The gods implored Parvati (Sati\'s reincarnation), daughter of the mountain king Himavan, to win Shiva\'s heart. She performed extreme austerities (tapas) next to him, but he remained unmoved. The god of love, Kama, shot his arrow of desire at Shiva, who in rage incinerated Kama with his third eye. Parvati\'s unwavering devotion eventually moved Shiva. He tested her in the guise of an old Brahmin, criticizing Shiva. Parvati defended him fiercely, proving her love. Convinced, Shiva married her. Their union produced the warrior god Kartikeya, who slew Tarakasura, and the wise Ganesha. The myth celebrates bhakti (devotion) as the force that can soften even the hardest ascetic heart and establishes the ideal of divine complementarity (Shiva\'s transcendence with Parvati\'s immanence).', 5, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(64, 'The Rape of the Sabine Women', 'The foundational (and problematic) Roman legend explaining how the early city of Romulus secured its future. After founding Rome, Romulus and his band of mostly male followers lacked wives. He invited the neighboring Sabine people to a festival. At a signal, the Romans abducted the young Sabine women, fighting off the men. Romulus promised the women rights and honorable marriages. When the Sabine king Titus Tatius later marched on Rome, the women—now mothers of Roman children—intervened, pleading for peace between their fathers and husbands. A treaty was struck, uniting the Romans and Sabines under joint rule. The legend, while justifying an act of violence, ultimately emphasizes reconciliation, integration, and the role of women as peace-weavers and mothers of a new, blended nation.', 3, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(65, 'The Prophecy of the Twelve Vultures', 'An augury legend surrounding Rome\'s founding. As Romulus and Remus disputed where to build their city—Romulus on the Palatine Hill, Remus on the Aventine—they agreed to seek a sign from the gods through bird-watching (auspicium). Remus first saw six vultures (or eagles, in some versions). Then Romulus saw twelve. Each claimed victory: Remus for seeing the omen first, Romulus for seeing the greater number. The dispute turned violent, leading to Remus\'s death (either by Romulus\'s hand or that of his lieutenant, Celer). The twelve vultures were interpreted as a divine sign that Rome would endure for twelve centuries (a prophecy later retrofitted to fit the empire\'s timeline). The story underscores the importance of divination in Roman statecraft and the fatal rivalry that marked the city\'s bloody, destined beginning.', 3, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(66, 'The Sleep of Silvanus', 'A historical legend from the Gallic sack of Rome (c. 390 BCE). The Gauls, having routed the Roman army, besieged the Capitoline Hill, the last refuge. One night, they attempted a stealthy ascent. The Romans\' watchdogs failed to bark. However, the sacred geese of Juno, kept on the hill, heard the invaders and cackled loudly, awakening the former consul Marcus Manlius. He roused the defenders and repelled the Gauls, saving the citadel. The legend, recorded by Livy, served to explain the survival of Roman state religion and identity. It led to the annual ritual of crucifying a dog and parading a goose in honor, contrasting the punishment of the negligent dogs with the reward for the vigilant geese, symbolizing divine protection through unexpected means.', 3, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(67, 'Etana and the Eagle', 'An ancient Mesopotamian myth from Sumer/Akkad. Etana, a king, was childless and prayed for an heir. He rescued an eagle that had been trapped in a pit by a serpent (after betraying an oath). In gratitude, the eagle carried Etana on its back high into the sky to find the "plant of birth" (or sometimes to plead before the gods). As they ascended, Etana looked down and grew terrified by the diminishing earth. The eagle reassured him, but in some fragmented versions, they may have fallen. The ending is unclear, but it\'s believed Etana succeeded and secured a dynasty. The tale explores themes of kingship, divine favor, interdependency between man and animal, and the human fear of striving for the heavens.', 6, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(68, 'Adapa and the South Wind', 'A Babylonian wisdom myth about the loss of immortality. Adapa, the sage of Eridu created by Ea (Enki), was fishing when the South Wind capsized his boat. In anger, he "broke the wing of the South Wind," stopping it from blowing. The sky god Anu summoned him to explain. Ea, fearing for his creation, advised Adapa to wear mourning clothes and blame his actions on the death of two gods in the sea. He also warned him not to eat or drink anything offered in heaven, as it would be the food of death. Anu, impressed by Adapa\'s appearance and story, offered instead the food and water of life (immortality). Remembering Ea\'s warning, Adapa refused. Anu, laughing at the trick played on him by Ea, sent Adapa back to mortal earth. The myth explains human mortality as the result of following deceptive divine advice and missing a one-time chance at eternal life.', 6, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(69, 'Nergal and Ereshkigal', 'A Mesopotamian myth of diplomacy and underworld marriage. When the goddess Ereshkigal, queen of the underworld (Kur), could not attend a celestial banquet, the gods sent a messenger, Kakka. She demanded a proper envoy. The war god Nergal was sent, instructed not to partake of any underworld offerings. He violated the rule, and when Ereshkigal rose from her throne to bathe, he was supposed to be seized, but instead, he seized her. They made love for six days. When Nergal returned to heaven, Ereshkigal threatened to raise the dead unless he returned. The gods sent him back, and he became her husband and co-ruler of the underworld, taking his place beside her on the throne. This myth establishes a balance of power, integrating the violent god of war and plague into the administration of death, ensuring the dead remain in their realm.', 6, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(70, 'The Curse of the Pyramid of Cheops', 'A modern legend, akin to Tutankhamun\'s curse, attached to the largest pyramid at Giza. It alleges that those who enter its hidden chambers, particularly the so-called "secret room" or the "King\'s Chamber," risk invoking an ancient curse. Tales speak of archaeologists, tourists, or even Napoleon\'s soldiers suffering from sudden illness, freak accidents, or death shortly after their visit. The legend is fueled by the pyramid\'s immense, mysterious scale, its precise but unknown construction methods, and the general aura of the "forbidden." While scientifically baseless, it thrives on the human tendency to associate awe-inspiring ancient monuments with protective supernatural power, warning against the hubris of penetrating their last secrets.', 1, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(71, 'The Journey of the Solar Barque', 'The central Egyptian theological concept of the sun\'s cyclical rebirth. Each night, the sun god Ra (or Re) traveled through the twelve regions of the Duat (underworld) in his barque, Mandjet. He was accompanied by a crew of gods (like Sia, Heka, and Ma\'at) and defended by other deities. The journey was a perilous passage through a landscape of demons and pits of fire. The greatest threat was the gigantic serpent of chaos, Apep (Apophis), who attempted to swallow the barque and stop the sun\'s rebirth. Ra and his defenders, especially the god Set who wielded a spear from the boat\'s prow, fought and vanquished Apep each night. At dawn, Ra emerged triumphant from the eastern mountains, reborn as Khepri, the scarab beetle. This myth visualized the triumph of order (Ma\'at) over chaos (Isfet) as a daily, necessary event, ensuring the continuity of life.', 1, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(72, 'The Rebellion of Seth', 'The detailed narrative of the conflict between Horus and Set (see Legend #26). This is a duplicate or closely related entry focusing on Set\'s act of rebellion against the divine order by murdering his brother Osiris and his subsequent war against the rightful heir, Horus. It details the 80-year struggle, the gods\' council, the battles, and Set\'s final defeat and banishment to the arid periphery of the world, cementing his role as the necessary antagonist in the Egyptian cosmic drama.', 1, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(73, 'The Judgment of Anubis', 'The definitive Egyptian vision of the afterlife. Upon death, the ba (soul) would journey to the Hall of Ma\'at for judgment. Anubis would lead the deceased before Osiris and a tribunal of 42 judges. The heart (ib), seat of conscience and memory, was placed on a scale against the feather of Ma\'at (truth/order). Thoth recorded the result. If the heart was heavy with sin, it was devoured by the monster Ammit, resulting in the "second death" (total annihilation). If it balanced, the deceased was declared "true of voice" and welcomed into the blissful Field of Reeds (Aaru). The ritual was guided by spells in the Book of the Dead. This concept made ethics central to salvation, promising a moral afterlife based on one\'s earthly deeds, a powerful incentive for living a just life.', 1, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(74, 'The Prophecy of Nefertiti', 'A modern fabricated legend with no basis in historical texts. It claims the famed queen and wife of Akhenaten prophesied that her tomb (which remains undiscovered) would lie hidden for millennia and bring immense fortune to its discoverer. This "legend" is a product of 20th-century Egyptomania and the romantic mystery surrounding Nefertiti\'s life, death, and missing burial place. It reflects the public\'s desire to attach prophetic significance to unsolved archaeological mysteries and mirrors the narrative of Tutankhamun\'s curse, but inverted as a blessing.', 1, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(75, 'The Werewolf of Bray Road', 'A modern American cryptid from Elkhorn, Wisconsin, reported since the 1980s. Described as a muscular, bipedal wolf-like creature (a "werewolf" or "dogman") standing 5-7 feet tall. It is often seen walking upright along Bray Road and has been reported to chase cars. It\'s a classic example of a localized monster legend that blends the ancient werewolf archetype with contemporary roadside encounter reports.', 15, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(76, 'The Labyrinth of the Minotaur', 'The Cretan Labyrinth, designed by the master craftsman Daedalus for King Minos, was an impenetrable, maze-like prison beneath the palace of Knossos. Its sole purpose was to contain the monstrous Minotaur, born from Queen Pasiphaë\'s union with a bull. Every nine years, as tribute for the death of his son Androgeos, Athens sent seven youths and seven maidens to be devoured by the creature. The Athenian hero Theseus volunteered to end this horror. Upon arriving in Crete, King Minos\'s daughter Ariadne fell in love with him. She provided him with a ball of thread (the "clew," giving us the word "clue") and a sword. Theseus tied one end of the thread at the entrance, ventured into the winding, dark corridors, slew the Minotaur at its heart, and then retraced his steps by following the thread back to freedom. This legend symbolizes the triumph of Athenian heroism and clever planning over Cretan tyranny and monstrous chaos, and establishes the labyrinth as the archetypal symbol for a complex, inescapable problem.', 2, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(77, 'The Punishment of Prometheus', 'A foundational myth about the origins of civilization and divine retribution. The Titan Prometheus, a champion of humanity, tricked Zeus during a sacrificial feast, securing the best meat for humans. Later, he committed the ultimate transgression: he ascended to Olympus and stole fire from the gods\' hearth, hiding it in a fennel stalk to give to humanity, enabling progress, craft, and culture. Enraged, Zeus ordered Hephaestus to chain Prometheus to a rock in the Caucasus Mountains. There, an eagle (or a vulture) would visit him daily to devour his liver, which regenerated each night due to his immortality, making his torment eternal. Prometheus endured this agony for ages until he was finally freed by the hero Heracles. The myth explores themes of sacrifice for humanity\'s sake, the cost of knowledge and technology, and the brutal price of defiance against absolute power.', 2, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(78, 'The Abduction of Europa', 'A story of divine seduction and the naming of a continent. Europa, a Phoenician princess of great beauty, was gathering flowers with her companions when Zeus spotted her. Smitten, he transformed himself into a magnificent, gentle white bull with horns like a crescent moon. The bull was so tame that Europa approached, adorned it with garlands, and eventually climbed onto its back. Suddenly, the bull charged into the sea and swam across the Mediterranean to the island of Crete. There, Zeus revealed his true form, and Europa became the first queen of Crete, bearing him three sons: Minos, Rhadamanthys, and Sarpedon. The continent of Europe is named after her. This myth explains the Phoenician (Eastern) cultural influence on Crete and serves as an origin story for the Minoan dynasty, linking it directly to Zeus.', 2, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(79, 'The Calydonian Boar Hunt', 'A tale of a failed sacrifice leading to epic collaboration and tragic rivalry. King Oineus of Calydon forgot to include Artemis in his harvest offerings. In wrath, the goddess sent a gigantic, destructive boar to ravage his kingdom. To deal with the menace, Oineus\' son, the hero Meleager, gathered a band of Greece\'s greatest heroes, including Jason, Castor and Pollux, Theseus, and Atalanta, the formidable huntress. Meleager was smitten with Atalanta. During the hunt, she drew first blood. Ultimately, Meleager delivered the killing blow. He awarded the boar\'s hide (the prize) to Atalanta, sparking jealousy among his uncles, who claimed the trophy belonged to the family. In the ensuing quarrel, Meleager killed them. His mother, Althaea, in a fit of vengeance for her brothers, burned the magical log that was tied to Meleager\'s life from birth, causing his death. The hunt highlights themes of honor, the wrath of the gods, and the fatal consequences of familial strife.', 2, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(80, 'The Theft of the Golden Knobs', 'A crucial Norse myth about the source of the gods\' immortality. The goddess Idunn guarded golden apples in a casket; by eating them, the gods maintained their eternal youth. The giant Thjazi, in the form of a great eagle, tricked Loki into promising to deliver Idunn and her apples to him. Loki lured Idunn into a forest, where Thjazi snatched her and flew to his home, Thrymheim. The gods began to age rapidly without the apples. They threatened Loki, who borrowed Freya\'s falcon cloak, flew to Jotunheim, transformed Idunn into a nut, and carried her back in his claws. Thjazi gave chase as an eagle, but the gods lit a fire around Asgard\'s walls. Thjazi\'s feathers caught flame, and he fell, where he was killed by the gods. This story underscores the vulnerability of the gods and Loki\'s role as both problem-creator and problem-solver, essential yet treacherous.', 4, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(81, 'The Death of Baldr', 'The central Norse tragedy. The beloved god Baldr is tormented by dreams of his death. His mother, Frigg, secures oaths from all things in creation not to harm him, overlooking the mistletoe as too young. The trickster Loki fashions a dart from mistletoe and guides the hand of the blind god Höðr, who kills Baldr. This act is the pivotal event that sets the irreversible course toward Ragnarök, as it breaks the peace and goodness of Asgard.', 4, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(82, 'The Birth of Sleipnir', 'A bizarre tale of Loki\'s shapeshifting and the origin of Odin\'s steed. A giant builder offered to build an impregnable wall around Asgard in exchange for the sun, the moon, and the goddess Freyja. The gods, thinking the task impossible, agreed but gave him only one winter, with no outside help. The builder had a massive stallion, Svaðilfari, who did the work of ten. With the deadline nearing, the worried gods forced Loki to sabotage the project. Loki transformed into a beautiful mare and lured the stallion away into the woods. The builder failed to finish on time and was killed by Thor. Later, Loki returned to Asgard, having given birth to an eight-legged foal, Sleipnir, the finest horse ever to exist. He gave it to Odin. Sleipnir, meaning "The Sliding One," could travel between worlds, over sea, and through air. This myth showcases Loki\'s ambiguous nature and provides a fantastical origin for Odin\'s primary mount.', 4, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(83, 'Andvari\'s Treasure', 'The foundational curse that drives the entire Volsung cycle and Wagner\'s Ring. The dwarf Andvari guarded a vast hoard of gold, including a magical ring, Andvaranaut, that could multiply wealth. The gods Odin, Loki, and Hœnir killed Otr, a son of King Hreidmar, who was in otter form. As compensation, Hreidmar demanded enough gold to fill and cover the otter\'s skin. Loki captured Andvari and took all his gold, including the ring. Andvari, enraged, cursed the ring and the gold: it would bring death and destruction to all who possessed it. The curse played out tragically: Hreidmar was killed by his son Fafnir, who turned into a dragon to guard the hoard. Fafnir was slain by Sigurd (Siegfried), who then fell victim to the curse himself. This is the quintessential "cursed treasure" myth, exploring the corrupting nature of greed and the inescapability of fate.', 4, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(84, 'The Prophecy of the Norns', 'The Norse personifications of fate, the three Norns (Urðr, Verðandi, Skuld—Past, Present, and Future) dwell by the Well of Urðr beneath Yggdrasil. They weave the tapestry of fate (ørlög) for gods and men. Their most famous prophecy is the foretelling of Ragnarök, which they see inscribed in the runes and reflected in the disturbed waters of the well. They predict the death of Baldr, the breaking of bonds (Fenrir, Loki), the Fimbulwinter, and the final battle. Unlike Greek Fates, the Norns\' prophecies are not always irrevocable decrees but powerful currents of destiny that even the gods must heed. Their existence introduces a layer of profound fatalism into Norse mythology, where even the Allfather Odin seeks knowledge from them but cannot change the woven threads.', 4, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(85, 'The Curse of Macha', 'A dark Irish tale of cruelty and supernatural punishment. Macha, a goddess of sovereignty and war, came to live with the widower Cruinniuc, disguising her nature. When she became pregnant, Cruinniuc boasted at a royal assembly that his wife could outrun the king\'s finest horses. The king, hearing this, forced the heavily pregnant Macha to race. She begged for a delay but was refused. She ran and won, but at the finish line, she gave birth to twins and screamed a curse upon the men of Ulster: that in their hour of greatest need, they would be stricken with the weakness of a woman in childbirth for five days and four nights. This curse, the Ces Noinden, plays a crucial role in the Táin Bó Cúailnge, leaving only the teenaged Cú Chulainn unaffected to defend Ulster. The curse represents the violation of hospitality (geis) and the terrible power of a wronged woman.', 7, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(86, 'The Cauldron of Dagda', 'One of the Four Treasures of the Tuatha Dé Danann, the Dagda\'s cauldron (Coire Ansic) was a vessel of endless plenty and a tool of resurrection. It was said that no company ever left it unsatisfied. In some versions, particularly those involving the Welsh figure Bran the Blessed (from which this description may blend), it had the power to restore the dead to life. However, those resurrected would be mute, as they had seen the other side and could not speak of it. This cauldron represents the Dagda\'s role as a provider and protector of the tribe, ensuring both physical sustenance and a form of eternal, if limited, return from death.', 7, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(87, 'The Escape of Oisín', 'The poignant conclusion of the Oisín and Niamh story. After what feels like three years in the Land of Youth, Oisín returns to Ireland on Niamh\'s magical horse, warned not to dismount. He finds the Ireland of the Fianna gone, replaced by small men and Christianity. Helping some men move a stone, he falls from the saddle. Instantly, the centuries catch up with him, and he ages into a withered ancient. Before dying, he tells his story to Saint Patrick, symbolizing the passing of the pagan heroic age into Christian history.', 7, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(88, 'The Stone of Destiny', 'One of the Four Treasures of the Tuatha Dé Danann, the Lia Fáil ("Stone of Destiny" or "Speaking Stone") was a coronation stone brought from their mythical cities. It was placed on the Hill of Tara, the seat of the High Kings of Ireland. The stone was said to let out a mighty roar that could be heard across the island when the true and rightful king stood upon it or drove his chariot over it. Its cry confirmed the king\'s divine right to rule. The legend embodies the sacred connection between the rightful sovereign, the land itself, and the supernatural approval of the Tuatha Dé Danann. The historical Stone of Scone, used in British coronations, is sometimes linked to this myth.', 7, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(89, 'The Battle of the Bulls', 'The central epic of the Ulster Cycle. The conflict begins with a pillow-talk quarrel between Queen Medb of Connacht and her husband Ailill over who has greater wealth. The only difference is Ailill\'s supremely fertile white-horned bull, Finnbhennach. To equal him, Medb seeks to obtain the even more magnificent Brown Bull of Cooley, Donn Cuailnge, from Ulster. When the owner refuses, Medb launches a massive invasion to seize it by force. The bulk of the Ulster warriors are incapacitated by the Curse of Macha, leaving the young hero Cú Chulainn to single-handedly hold the ford against Connacht\'s champions. After epic battles, Medb secures the bull. The two bulls meet and fight a cataclysmic battle across Ireland; the Brown Bull kills the White Bull but is mortally wounded, wandering the land before dying of exhaustion. The tale is less about cattle and more about pride, sovereignty, territorial conflict, and the superhuman defense of the homeland.', 7, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(90, 'The Fall of Tenochtitlán', 'According to Aztec chronicles recorded after the conquest, a series of eight terrible omens appeared in the decade before Cortés\'s arrival, foretelling the collapse of Moctezuma II\'s empire. These included: a comet like a "spinning spindle of fire" in the sky; the spontaneous burning of Huitzilopochtli\'s temple; a lightning strike on another temple; the appearance of a strange two-headed bird; the waters of Lake Texcoco boiling and flooding; a weeping woman heard at night ("La Llorona"); a strange creature caught in a net; and, most chillingly, distorted men with two heads appearing in the streets who would vanish when shown to the emperor. These omens, likely a post-conquest narrative device, served to frame the Spanish arrival not as a random event but as a fated, supernatural cataclysm, the inevitable end of the Fifth Sun.', 9, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(91, 'The Sacrifice of Copil', 'A foundational legend for the Mexica (Aztecs). Copil, son of the sorceress Malinalxochitl (sister of Huitzilopochtli), sought revenge against his uncle for abandoning his mother. He rallied cities against the migrating Mexica. Huitzilopochtli\'s priests captured and sacrificed Copil on a hill near Lake Texcoco. His heart was thrown into the lake. From the spot where it landed, a prickly pear cactus (nopal) grew. Years later, the Mexica, fulfilling their patron god\'s prophecy, arrived at that same lake and saw an eagle perched on the nopal, devouring a serpent (or a precious bird). This vision identified the site for their great city, Tenochtitlan, which appears on the modern Mexican flag. The myth justifies the city\'s location through divine signs and ancestral sacrifice.', 9, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(92, 'The Legend of the Five Suns', 'The core Aztec cosmogonic narrative. The universe has undergone five creations, each called a "Sun," each ruled by a different deity and destroyed by a different cataclysm: 1) Jaguar Sun (destroyed by jaguars), 2) Wind Sun (destroyed by hurricanes), 3) Rain of Fire Sun (destroyed by volcanic fire), 4) Water Sun (destroyed by flood). We live in the 5th Sun, Nahui Ollin ("Movement"), which will be destroyed by earthquakes. The myth explains cosmic cycles, justifies the need for human sacrifice (to nourish and delay the end of the current Sun), and places humanity in a precarious, existential position.', 9, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(93, 'The Journey of Huitzilopochtli', 'The Mexica origin story. They began as a humble tribe from the mythical northern homeland, Aztlán. Their patron god, Huitzilopochtli ("Hummingbird of the South"), spoke to them through priests, commanding them to leave and seek a promised land. He guided them on a long, arduous migration lasting centuries. The journey was marked by stops, conflicts, and schisms (like the separation of the group led by Huitzilopochtli\'s sister, Malinalxochitl). The god provided signs and tests, such as the transformation of his idol into a hummingbird to indicate the correct path. The migration culminated in the vision of the eagle and cactus on the lake, where Huitzilopochtli commanded them to settle and build their city, Tenochtitlan. This legend served as a charter myth, justifying their right to the land and their identity as the "People of the Sun."', 9, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(94, 'The Birth of Mixcoatl', 'The "Cloud Serpent," a god of hunting, the Milky Way, and the starry sky. His origins are ancient and part of the complex Toltec and Chichimec mythologies later adopted by the Aztecs. In one version, during the creation of the world, a sacred bird shed a single feather that fell from the heavens. From this celestial feather, Mixcoatl was born. He is often considered the father of Quetzalcoatl and a deity who brought fire to humanity by creating the first fire drill from the heavens. As a god of the hunt, he was associated with the nomadic, pre-sedentary past and the starry paths hunters followed. His myth connects the celestial realm with the earthly necessities of survival.', 9, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(95, 'The Descent of Oya', 'Oya (Yansa) is the powerful Yoruba orisha of wind, storms, lightning, and the cemetery gates. Her "descent" refers to her role as a transformative force that comes to earth. She is said to have descended from the heavens to teach humanity how to harness and respect the power of the tempest. She controls the whirlwind and the sudden, violent change that clears away the old to make way for the new. As the wife of Shango, she accompanies his thunder with her fierce winds. Her descent is not a one-time event but a continual manifestation of her power in tornadoes, gust fronts, and the electric charge of the air before a storm. She represents the necessary, disruptive force of change and the guardian of the transition between life and death.', 10, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(96, 'The Creation of the Drum', 'In many African traditions, the drum is not just an instrument but a divine voice, a means of communication with the spirit world. Myths vary, but a common theme is that the first drum was created by the gods or a culture hero to bridge heaven and earth. In some stories, it was fashioned from a sacred tree and the skin of a primordial animal, its rhythms mimicking the heartbeat of the earth or the speech of the gods. The drum\'s sound could call the orishas to possess their devotees, send messages over long distances, or regulate the rhythms of community life. Its creation myth underscores the central role of music, rhythm, and oral tradition in African spirituality and social cohesion.', 10, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(97, 'The Escape of Anansi', 'The classic Akan tale where the trickster spider Anansi completes four impossible tasks set by the sky god Nyame—capturing a python, leopard, hornets, and a fairy—to purchase all the stories in the world. He succeeds through cunning, not strength, and brings the stories down to earth, which thereafter are called Anansesem (Spider Stories). This establishes Anansi as a culture hero and explains why wisdom and narrative belong to humanity.', 10, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(98, 'The Curse of Shango', 'Shango, the fiery orisha of thunder and justice, is known for his powerful temper. The legend holds that he placed a curse on anyone who dared to mimic or disrespect the sacred sound of his bàtá drums, which are used to call him and communicate his will. Imitating the complex, rapid rhythms (conversations) of the bàtá was seen as mocking the god\'s voice and authority. The curse could bring sudden misfortune, illness, or being struck by lightning. This taboo reinforced the sacred nature of the ritual music and the dangerous, awe-inspiring power of the deity it invoked, ensuring that only trained and initiated priests (olúbàtá) could handle this divine communication.', 10, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(99, 'The Journey of Yemaya', 'Yemaya (Yemoja), the mother orisha of the oceans and all life, is often depicted as a great traveler. Her journey is the constant, nurturing, yet powerful movement of the sea. She crossed the Atlantic with the enslaved Africans, becoming a central figure in the African diaspora. Mythically, she journeys from her deep ocean palace to the shores, bringing fertility, washing away sorrows, and sometimes unleashing her tempestuous waves when angered. Her journey is cyclical, like the tides, representing the flow of life, the connection between Africa and the New World, and the protective, enveloping journey of motherhood.', 10, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(100, 'The Creation of Hawaii', 'The volcanic origin of Hawaii is attributed to the goddess Pele. Driven from her ancestral home in Tahiti (often called Kahiki) by conflict with her sister, the sea goddess Namakaokaha\'i, Pele traveled north in search of a new home. She would strike the earth with her magical digging stick, Pa\'oa, to create a fire pit. Her sister would pursue and flood it with seawater. This chase created a chain of islands. She first created islands in the northwest (now the older, extinct Emperor Seamounts) before finally settling on the Big Island of Hawaii, where she made her eternal home in the fire pit of Halema\'uma\'u at Kilauea. The myth provides a divine, dramatic explanation for the archipelago\'s geological hotspot progression.', 11, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(101, 'The Battle of Kāmohoaliʻi', 'Kāmohoaliʻi, the shark god and brother of Pele, was the king of all sharks and a skilled navigator. In one legend, he and the trickster hero Māui engaged in a fierce battle for control over the fishing grounds and the seas around Hawaii. Māui, seeking to benefit humanity, wanted to ensure safe fishing. The battle was epic, with Kāmohoaliʻi summoning sharks and storms, and Māui using his cunning and magical fishhook. The outcome varies, but often it ends in a stalemate or an agreement, establishing boundaries between the realms of humans and the powerful shark deity. This myth highlights the respect given to sharks and the constant negotiation between humans and the potent forces of the ocean.', 11, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(102, 'The Legend of the Tiki', 'Tiki are carved humanoid figures representing deified ancestors or gods (like Tiki, the first man in Māori myth). In Polynesian belief, the first tiki were created by the gods themselves. The gods fashioned these statues as receptacles (waka) for their mana (spiritual power) and as guardians. They were placed in sacred spaces (marae, heiau) and villages to protect the people, ensure fertility, and mark tribal boundaries. The act of carving a tiki was a sacred ritual, and the finished statue was believed to be imbued with the spirit of the ancestor or deity it represented. They are not idols to be worshipped, but vessels of presence and protection.', 11, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(103, 'The Flight of Hina', 'Hina, the Polynesian goddess associated with the moon, tapa cloth, and women\'s crafts, is often a figure who seeks escape. In one widespread myth, tired of her demanding or abusive husband (sometimes the eel-god Kuna, sometimes a mortal), she climbs a rainbow or a spider\'s web to the moon. There, she finds eternal peace and is often seen beating tapa cloth. Her flight explains the markings on the moon and symbolizes refuge, feminine autonomy, and the desire to transcend earthly toil.', 11, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(104, 'The Curse of Kū', 'Kū, the Hawaiian god of war, politics, and deep forests, was a fierce and potent deity. His weapons and regalia were deeply kapu (taboo). The legend states that anyone who dared to steal or even touch his sacred weapons—such as his spear or his feathered kāhili (standard)—without permission would be struck by his curse. This curse could manifest as sudden illness, madness, defeat in battle, or the withering of one\'s crops and livelihood. The severity of the curse reinforced the sacred power (mana) of the god and the absolute authority of the aliʻi (chiefs) who were his descendants, ensuring that symbols of sovereignty and martial power were treated with utmost reverence.', 11, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(105, 'The Ghost of Abraham Lincoln', 'The most famous presidential ghost in American folklore. Lincoln\'s spirit has been reported by numerous people in the White House, most frequently in the Lincoln Bedroom and the Yellow Oval Room. Eleanor Roosevelt and Winston Churchill reportedly sensed his presence. Queen Wilhelmina of the Netherlands claimed to have seen his ghost in a hallway. The legend is fueled by Lincoln\'s tragic assassination, his deep connection to the nation\'s fate, and the White House\'s long history as a seat of power and drama, making it a prime location for a lingering, protective presence.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(106, 'The Prophecy of the White Buffalo', 'A central Lakota prophecy linked to the White Buffalo Calf Woman. When she departed, she said she would return in a time of great need. Her return is tied to the birth of a rare white buffalo calf. Each such birth is seen as a potent sign, a renewal of her sacred promise. The birth of a white buffalo (like "Miracle" in 1994) is interpreted as a sign of hope, a call for prayer and unity, and a harbinger of a new era of peace and spiritual awakening for all nations. It is a living legend that continues to unfold.', 12, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(107, 'The Journey of Coyote', 'A widespread Native American trickster tale. In the beginning, fire was guarded by beings far away (the gods, the Fire People, or on a distant mountain). Coyote, seeing humans suffering in the cold, devised a plan. He gathered animal friends for a relay race. Through trickery—often distracting the guardians with a game or a dance—Coyote stole a burning brand. He and the animals (like Fox, Squirrel, or Frog) passed it along, with each animal\'s characteristics explaining their appearance today (e.g., Frog\'s back was burned, making it bumpy). Coyote delivered fire to humanity, establishing his role as a flawed but essential culture hero who brings vital knowledge through mischief.', 12, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(108, 'The Creation of the Raven', 'A Northwest Coast myth where Raven, originally pure white, is blackened while stealing the sun, moon, or fire. Flying too close to the celestial bodies or through the smoke hole of the house where they were kept, his feathers are scorched and sooted, leaving him forever black, sometimes with a few white feathers remaining as a reminder of his former beauty. It\'s a classic etiological tale from the trickster cycle.', 12, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(109, 'The Legend of the Three Brothers', 'A common archetype in Native American myths where cultural gifts are distributed. In various forms, three brothers (or sometimes heroes) go on a journey or are visited by the Great Spirit. Each receives a gift essential for the people\'s survival and way of life: the bow and arrow (for hunting and defense), the sacred pipe (for prayer, peace, and communion with the spirit world), and the drum (for ceremony, communication, and community heartbeat). These gifts form the foundation of physical, spiritual, and social life, symbolizing the interconnected responsibilities of the warrior, the holy person, and the community.', 12, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(110, 'The Escape of the Monkey Queen', 'The epic backstory of the Monkey King from Journey to the West. After attaining great powers, Sun Wukong caused havoc in Heaven. He ate the Peaches of Immortality, drank the Jade Emperor\'s wine, and stole Laozi\'s pills of longevity, becoming virtually indestructible. He defied the celestial army and inscribed his name on the pillars of the universe. Finally, the Buddha intervened. He bet Sun Wukong he could not leap out of his palm. The Monkey King somersaulted to the end of the world, marked a pillar, and returned. The Buddha showed him his hand: the "pillar" was the Buddha\'s finger. For his hubris, Sun Wukong was imprisoned under Five Elements Mountain for 500 years, to be later released for the pilgrimage. This legend establishes Sun Wukong\'s incredible power and pride, and the even greater power that can contain it.', 13, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(111, 'The Legend of the Golden Dragon', 'A Chinese myth about the origin of the Yellow River (Huang He). A compassionate golden dragon, witnessing a great drought and famine on the North China Plain, sacrificed itself for the people. It plunged into the earth, its body transforming into the winding course of the great river, its golden scales becoming the fertile yellow silt (loess) that gives the river its color and name. The river\'s floods, while sometimes destructive, are seen as the dragon\'s continued movement, bringing life-giving water and soil. This myth explains the river\'s vital, unpredictable nature and links it to a benevolent, self-sacrificing celestial being.', 13, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(112, 'The Weaver\'s Marriage', 'The love story between the celestial weaver Zhinü (Vega) and the mortal cowherd Niulang (Altair), separated by the Milky Way and allowed to meet only once a year on the 7th day of the 7th lunar month, when magpies form a bridge. This is the basis for the Qixi Festival.', 13, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(113, 'The Curse of the Nine-Tailed Fox', 'A legendary episode from the fall of the Shang Dynasty. The last Shang king, King Zhou, was led to ruin by his beautiful concubine Daji. She was said to be possessed by a malicious nine-tailed fox spirit (huli jing), sent by the gods to punish the king\'s corruption. Daji encouraged horrific cruelty, extravagant debauchery, and the torture and execution of loyal ministers. Her influence drained the dynasty\'s virtue (de), leading to its overthrow by the Zhou. The story is a classic "femme fatale" narrative in Chinese historiography, using a demonic fox spirit to explain political collapse and moral decay.', 13, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(114, 'The Curse of the Altamura Mummy', 'A local Italian legend from Altamura, Puglia. In the 19th century, the mummified body of a young man was found sealed in the wall of a palace. It became a macabre tourist attraction. A legend grew that photographing the mummy would bring bad luck or death to the photographer. This is a classic "cursed object" tale on a local scale, similar to Tutankhamun but much more contained, reflecting the taboo and unease surrounding the display of human remains.', 15, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(115, 'The Dance of Jarilo', 'Jarilo is the Slavic god of vegetation, fertility, spring, and war. His annual "dance" represents the return of life after winter. In spring rituals, a young man adorned with greenery and flowers would represent Jarilo, dancing through villages and fields. His dance was believed to transfer his vitality to the earth, ensuring fertile soil and abundant harvests. The rituals often involved processions, singing, and symbolic marriage to the goddess of death/winter, Morana, whose effigy was later destroyed or cast into water. Jarilo\'s dance symbolizes the joyful, vigorous, and necessary rebirth of the natural world.', 14, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(116, 'Kupala Night', 'A major Slavic folk holiday celebrated on the summer solstice (June 23-24), merging pagan and Christian (St. John the Baptist) elements. It was believed that on this magical night, the boundaries between the worlds were thin. Ferns would bloom with a fiery flower that granted the finder the ability to see treasure, understand animal speech, and become invisible. Young people would jump over bonfires for purification and fortune, and girls would float wreaths with candles on rivers to predict their love life. Spirits of the forest and water were especially active. The holiday celebrates fertility, love, and the peak of solar power, full of divination and connections to the supernatural.', 14, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(117, 'The Curse of Baba Yaga', 'Baba Yaga, the ambiguous witch of Slavic folklore, is the guardian of the border between the everyday world and the magical forest. Her curse falls upon those who enter her domain without permission, respect, or a just cause. The curse could take many forms: being lost forever in the ever-shifting forest, transformed into an animal or object, or simply being caught, cooked, and eaten. However, her "curse" is also a test. Those who approach her hut correctly (addressing it with the traditional incantation), show courage and cleverness in answering her riddles, and perform her tasks, may receive magical aid. Her power represents the peril and potential reward of venturing into the unknown.', 14, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(118, 'The Treasure of the Zmey', 'A classic Slavic folktale motif. A zmey (dragon) often hoards vast treasures in a cave deep within a mountain or under a lake. The treasure is usually gold, silver, and jewels, but sometimes includes magical items or captive princesses. A hero, often a simple peasant\'s son named Ivan, must slay the multi-headed beast (usually by cutting off all its heads, which regrow unless the root is burned) to win the treasure and free the captives. The dragon\'s treasure symbolizes ill-gotten wealth, the hoarding of resources, and the reward for courage in confronting a seemingly insurmountable embodiment of greed and evil.', 14, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(119, 'The Prophecy of Veles', 'Veles (Volos) is the Slavic god of the underworld, cattle, wealth, and magic, opposed to the thunder god Perun. As a chthonic deity connected to waters and the earth\'s depths, some fragmented legends or modern reconstructions suggest Veles possessed oracular knowledge. A prophecy attributed to him might foretell a time when his watery domain would overwhelm the world of order (Perun\'s sky), perhaps in a great flood or cataclysm that would reset the cosmic balance. This aligns with his role as a god of chaos, fertility, and the cyclical nature of destruction and rebirth, contrasting with Perun\'s structuring, celestial power.', 14, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(120, 'The Mystery of the Baigong Pipes', 'A modern mystery from Qinghai province, China. On Mount Baigong, there are reportedly three triangular caves containing what appear to be rusty iron pipes of varying diameters embedded in the rock, some leading to a nearby saltwater lake. Their origin is unknown. While some fringe theories suggest ancient aliens or a lost advanced civilization, geologists propose they are likely fossilized tree roots or natural geological formations (fulgurites or sinter pipes) that have been eroded and misinterpreted. The legend thrives on the internet as an "out-of-place artifact" mystery.', 13, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(121, 'The Phantom of the Opera', 'Based on the 1910 novel by Gaston Leroux, which itself was inspired by real events and legends at the Palais Garnier in Paris. The story tells of Erik, a disfigured musical genius who lives in the catacombs beneath the opera house. He becomes obsessed with the young singer Christine Daaé, mentoring her through a hidden wall and demanding she be the lead. His sabotage (including the famous chandelier crash) terrorizes the opera. While Leroux presented it as a true story, it is a work of fiction that synthesized tales of a real underground lake beneath the opera, a fatal accident with a counterweight, and rumors of a ghost. It has become one of the world\'s most enduring Gothic legends.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(122, 'The Legend of the Kraken', 'A legendary giant sea monster of Scandinavian folklore, said to dwell off the coasts of Norway and Greenland. Early accounts described it as a crab-like creature the size of a floating island. By the 18th century, it was depicted more as a gigantic squid or octopus that could drag entire ships and crews to the depths. The legend is now believed to have been inspired by real sightings of giant squid (Architeuthis). The Kraken embodies the terror of the unknown deep ocean and the vulnerability of sailors to forces beyond their comprehension.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(123, 'The Legend of El Chupacabra', 'Emerging from Puerto Rico in 1995, the "goat-sucker" is a modern Latin American cryptid blamed for mysterious livestock deaths, where animals are found drained of blood with puncture wounds. Early reports described a reptilian, bipedal creature with spines; later sightings often describe a hairless, dog-like beast. It has become a pan-Hispanic legend, reflecting anxieties about economic hardship, unexplained predation, and the unknown.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(124, 'The Ghost of the Queen Mary', 'The retired RMS Queen Mary, now a hotel and museum in Long Beach, California, is famously reported to be one of the world\'s most haunted ships. With a history spanning the golden age of ocean liners and WWII service as a troopship, many deaths occurred onboard. Reported phenomena include the sounds of splashing in the empty first-class pool, the ghost of a crewman crushed in Engine Room #13, and the spirit of a little girl in the nursery. Its immense size, rich history, and preserved Art Deco interiors make it a perfect canvas for spectral legends.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(125, 'The Curse of the Hope Diamond', 'A legendary curse attached to the 45.52-carat deep blue Hope Diamond. Its history is traced through owners who met misfortune: King Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette (guillotined); a Dutch merchant (killed by his son); heiress Evalyn Walsh McLean (her son died in a car crash, her daughter by suicide, her husband left her). The curse was largely popularized and exaggerated by jeweler Pierre Cartier to enhance the stone\'s mystique when selling it to McLean. While many tragedies are factual, their connection to the diamond is coincidental, creating a perfect template for a "cursed jewel" narrative.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(126, 'The Suicide Bridge of Tokyo', 'While not a single bridge, the Aokigahara Forest at the base of Mount Fuji, also known as the "Sea of Trees," is a tragically real location with a heavy legendary atmosphere. It is unfortunately known for a high number of suicides. Over time, Japanese media and folklore have woven legends around it, saying it is haunted by the yūrei (ghosts) of those who died there, who are said to wander the dense, sound-absorbing forest and may try to compel the living to join them. The legend serves as a dark, modern manifestation of traditional ghost stories tied to a specific, sorrowful place.', 8, 0, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(127, 'The Legend of Bloody Mary', 'A widespread Anglo-American ritual legend where chanting "Bloody Mary" in a dark mirror summons a vengeful spirit. Its origins are murky, possibly linked to Queen Mary I, folklore about mirrors capturing souls, or witchcraft.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(128, 'The Lost City of Atlantis', 'The original source is two dialogues by Plato (Timaeus and Critias), written around 360 BCE. He describes Atlantis as a powerful, advanced island kingdom beyond the "Pillars of Hercules" (Strait of Gibraltar) that sank into the ocean "in a single day and night of misfortune" after failing to conquer Athens. Plato likely used it as a philosophical allegory about hubris. Since then, it has been interpreted as a historical reality by countless writers, inspiring theories placing it everywhere from the Mediterranean to the Caribbean. It is the archetypal legend of a lost, utopian (or dystopian) civilization, representing humanity\'s fascination with sunken glory and forgotten origins.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(129, 'The 2012 Maya Prophecy', 'A major modern misinterpretation. As the Maya Long Count calendar completed a 5,125-year cycle on December 21, 2012, it was erroneously popularized (especially in New Age and doom-saying circles) as predicting the "end of the world." Maya scholars and epigraphers consistently stated the date marked a cyclical renewal, not an apocalypse. The legend grew from a mix of mistranslation, sensationalism, and the alignment of the date with astronomical phenomena (like the sun\'s alignment with the Milky Way\'s center). It serves as a prime example of how ancient calendars can be misconstrued to feed contemporary apocalyptic anxieties.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21'),
	(130, 'The Legend of the Holy Grail', 'The sacred cup used by Jesus at the Last Supper, and later by Joseph of Arimathea to catch his blood at the crucifixion. Entering European literature in the 12th century through Chrétien de Troyes and later the Vulgate Cycle, it became the ultimate object of quest for King Arthur\'s knights, particularly Percival and Galahad. It represents divine grace, purity, and the unattainable ideal. The legend has been interpreted as a Christianization of earlier Celtic cauldrons of plenty, and its mystery has inspired endless searches, theories, and stories, from medieval romance to Indiana Jones.', 15, 1, NULL, '2025-12-07 12:07:21');
